A. Title and Authors

CS 15 Project 4: gerp  
Romil Shah  
Belema Roberts

B. Purpose of the Program

The purpose of this program is to search through a directory of text files
efficiently. The program reads every file in the input directory tree, stores
the file paths and lines, and builds indexes so that later queries can be
answered quickly. It supports both case-sensitive and case-insensitive
searches, lets the user switch output files during execution, and prints the
matching file path, line number, and line text for each result.

C. Acknowledgements

We used the course specification, the provided starter files, and the
reference executable `the_gerp` as our main resources for this project. We
also used class material and the provided examples to help guide our
implementation and testing.

D. Files Provided and Their Purpose

main.cpp  
Contains the driver for the program. It checks command-line arguments, opens
the initial output file, creates the main data structures, builds the indexes,
and starts the query loop.

gerp.cpp  
Contains the main program logic. This file builds the indexes, processes
files, handles queries, and prints results.

gerp.h  
Header file for the helper functions implemented in gerp.cpp.

index.cpp  
Implements the `index` class. This class uses a hash table with separate
chaining to map words to the line IDs where they appear.

index.h  
Header file for the `index` class.

File_Storage.cpp  
Implements the `FileStorage` class, which stores file paths and line data.
This allows the program to store each line once and later recover the file
path, line number, and line text from a line ID.

File_Storage.h  
Header file for the `FileStorage` class.

processing.cpp  
Implements the Phase 1 helper functions, including directory traversal and
stripping non-alphanumeric characters from the front and back of tokens.

processing.h  
Header file for the processing helper functions.

Makefile  
Builds the gerp executable and includes the clean rule.

README  
This file.

E. How to Compile and Run the Program

To compile the program:
    make

To run the program:
    ./gerp inputDirectory outputFile

Example:
    ./gerp /comp/15/files/proj-gerp-test-dirs/tinyData out.txt

After the program starts, it will repeatedly print:
    Query?

The user may then enter:
- a normal word for case-sensitive search
- `@i word` for case-insensitive search
- `@insensitive word` for case-insensitive search
- `@f newOutputFile` to switch the output file
- `@q` or `@quit` to exit the program


F. Architectural Overview

The program is organized into a few main parts.

`main.cpp` is the driver. It checks for correct command-line arguments, opens
the initial output file, creates the main data structures, calls the index
building code, and then starts the query loop.

`gerp.cpp` contains most of the main logic of the program. It is responsible
for reading files, storing line information, building both the
case-sensitive and case-insensitive indexes, and processing user queries.

The `FileStorage` class stores the file paths and all line data. Each line is
stored once along with its line number and the index of the file path it came
from. This makes the program more space efficient because the full text of a
line does not need to be stored repeatedly inside the index.

The `index` class is used for fast lookup of words. It stores a word and the
line IDs where that word appears. We create two separate `index` objects:
one for case-sensitive search and one for case-insensitive search.

The `processing` module contains the helper functions from Phase 1, including
the function for stripping non-alphanumeric characters from the front and back
of tokens.

The overall flow of the program is:
1. Traverse the input directory tree.
2. Read every file and every line.
3. Store file paths and line data in `FileStorage`.
4. Insert words into the sensitive and insensitive indexes.
5. Enter the query loop and answer searches using the indexes.


G. Data Structures and Algorithms Used

The main data structures we used were vectors, sets, and a hash table
implemented using a vector of vectors.

In the `index` class, the hash table is implemented as a
`vector<vector<WordNode>>`. Each `WordNode` stores a word and a `vector<int>`
of line IDs where that word appears. We used separate chaining to handle
collisions, and the table resizes when the number of stored words gets too
large relative to the table size.

We used two index objects:
- one sensitive index
- one insensitive index

The sensitive index stores cleaned words exactly as they appear. The
insensitive index stores lowercase versions of cleaned words. This makes both
search types efficient because the program does not need to scan every stored
word when handling an insensitive query.

In `FileStorage`, file paths are stored in a `vector<string>`, and lines are
stored in a `vector<LineData>`. Each `LineData` stores:
- the line number
- the index of the file path
- the full line text

This design lets us store each line once and refer back to it using a line ID.

While building the index for a line, we use sets to avoid adding the same line
multiple times for the same word. One set is used for case-sensitive words and
one set is used for lowercase words. This prevents duplicate output lines when
a word appears multiple times on the same line.

The main algorithm is:
1. Recursively traverse the directory tree.
2. For each file, read line by line.
3. Split each line into tokens.
4. Strip non-alphanumeric characters from the front and back of each token.
5. Insert each unique word from that line into the correct indexes.
6. During queries, look up the word in the correct index and print the
   matching lines using the stored line IDs.

H. Testing

We tested the program in multiple stages.

For Phase 1, we tested the helper functions separately, especially
`stripNonAlphaNum`, with edge cases such as:
- punctuation only at the front
- punctuation only at the back
- punctuation on both sides
- punctuation in the middle
- strings that become empty after stripping

We also tested directory traversal on smaller directory structures.

For the full program, we tested by running our implementation against the
provided reference executable `the_gerp`. We tested:
- normal case-sensitive queries
- case-insensitive queries using `@i`
- queries that do not exist
- switching output files using `@f`
- quitting with `@q`
- tricky punctuation queries

For many tests, we compared our output files with the reference using `diff`.
When output order could vary, we sorted both output files before comparing
them. We also compared the standard output behavior when needed.

One issue we found during testing was how the program should behave when an
insensitive query becomes an empty string after stripping punctuation. Testing
against the reference helped us fix that case so that our output matched the
expected behavior.


I. Time Spent

We each spent approximately 5 hours on this project, so total time spent 
is 10 hours. This includes Phase 1, the design checkoff, implementation, 
debugging, testing against the reference, and final cleanup.